&nbsp;
   <p style="margin-left: 1.2in">
   <font size="+2">
   I want you to be
  <FONT color="red"><B>aware</B></FONT> of these
  <FONT color="blue"><B>facts</B></FONT>:
   </font>
   </p>

   <center>
   <TABLE bgcolor="lightcyan" BORDER="5" width=800>
   <TR> <TD>
   <font size="+2">
   <UL>

   <LI> <FONT color="red"><B><I>All</I> memory cells</B></FONT>
        are <FONT color="blue"><B>identical</B></FONT>: &nbsp;
        <FONT color="red"><B>each memory byte</B></FONT> stores
	<FONT color="blue"><B>8 bits (binary digits)</B></FONT>
 <P>
  <LI> <FONT color="blue"><B>That means:</B></FONT>
   &nbsp; to <FONT color="red"><B>define</B></FONT> a
       <FONT color="blue"><B><TT>byte</TT> typed variable</B></FONT>,
       we can <FONT color="red"><B>reserve 1 byte</B></FONT>
       <SPAN style="BACKGROUND-COLOR: #ffff00">
    <FONT color="blue"><B><I>anywhere</I></B></FONT></SPAN> in memory
   <P>
     (Because <FONT color="red"><B><I>all</I> memory cells</B></FONT> are
     <FONT color="blue"><B>identical</B></FONT> !)

   </UL>
   </font>
   </TD> </TR>
   </TABLE>
   </center>




   <p style="margin-left: 1.2in">
   <font size="+2">
 <SPAN style="BACKGROUND-COLOR: #ffff00">
   Then <FONT color="red"><B>how</B></FONT> do you
   <FONT color="blue"><B>distinguish</B></FONT>
   an <FONT color="red"><B><TT>int</TT> value</B></FONT> from
   a <FONT color="blue"><B><TT>float</TT> value </B></FONT> ???</SPAN>
   </font>
   </p>

   <center>
   <TABLE bgcolor="#CCFFCC" BORDER="5" width=800>
   <TR> <TD>
   <font size="+2">
   <UL>

   <LI> You must <FONT color="red"><B>use <I>different</I>
       computer <I>oprations</I></B></FONT> - the 
   <FONT color="blue"><B>computer</B></FONT> provides
    <FONT color="red"><B><TT>int-add</TT></B></FONT> and
    <FONT color="red"><B><TT>float-add</TT></B></FONT> operations !

   </UL>
   </font>
   </TD> </TR>
   </TABLE>
   </center>


   <p style="padding: 0.0in">
   </p>
