 <div class="mySlides">
   <div class="text">
   <FONT color="red" size=+2><B>
   <SPAN style="BACKGROUND-COLOR: yellow">
   Important pre-knowledge to understand variable definitions
   </SPAN>
   </B></FONT>
   </div>

&nbsp;
   <p style="margin-left: 1.2in">
   <font size="+2">
 <FONT color="red"><B>How</B></FONT> the
   <FONT color="blue"><B>computer</B></FONT>
   <FONT color="red"><B>distinguish</B></FONT>
    <FONT color="blue"><B>binary numbers</B></FONT> representing
    <FONT color="red"><B><I>different</I> data types</B></FONT>:
   </font>
   </p>

   <center>

<TABLE bgcolor="lightyellow" BORDER="5">
<TR> <TD>
 <font size="+2">
<FONT color="blue">
<B>
<PRE>
  <FONT color="red">int</FONT> data type: use <FONT color="red">int-typed operations</FONT> on data.

  Example:
                   00000000000000000000000000000010
          <FONT color="red">int-add</FONT>  11111111111111111111111111111111
        -------------------------------------------    
                   00000000000000000000000000000001
</PRE>
</B>
</FONT>
</FONT>
</TD> </TR>
</TABLE>

   </center>
<P>
&nbsp;
   <p style="margin-left: 1.2in">
   <font size="+2">
   Use a <FONT color="red"><B><TT>float-add</TT></B></FONT> 
    operation if you want to
    <FONT color="blue"><B>add</B></FONT>
    <FONT color="red"><B>floating point (IEEE 754)</B></FONT>
    representations.
   </font>
   </p>

   <p style="margin-left: 1.2in">
   <font size="+2">
   Every
     <FONT color="red"><B>CPU</B></FONT> has
   <FONT color="blue"><B><I>type-specific</I> arithmetic operations</B></FONT>
   !!!
   <BR>
    <A HREF="https://docs.oracle.com/cd/E18752_01/html/817-5477/ennbz.html#eoizh">
   Intel Integer instructions
   </A>
   <B>and</B>
   <A HREF="https://docs.oracle.com/cd/E18752_01/html/817-5477/eoizy.html">
   Intel Floating Point instructions
   </A>
   </font>
   </p>



